	<h1>Annotations</h1> 
	
	Tapestry doesn't just look for particular method names, it also looks for particular annotations. Here are some useful ones...<br/>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>@Property.</strong> If you put this annotation on a field then Tapestry will invisibly provide 
			a getter and setter for the field.<br/>  
			You can make the property read-only or write-only - 
			see <a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/5.3.6/apidocs/org/apache/tapestry5/annotations/Property.html">@Property</a>.<br/><br/></li>

		<li><strong>@OnEvent(value = EventConstants.ACTIVATE).</strong> You can put this annotation on a method instead of naming 
			the method <em>onActivate</em>.<br/><br/></li>
			
		<li><strong>@SetupRender.</strong> You can put this annotation on a method instead of naming the method 
			<em>setupRender</em>.<br/><br/></li>
			
		<li><strong>@CleanupRender.</strong> You can put this annotation on a method instead of naming the method 
			<em>cleanupRender</em>.<br/><br/></li>
			
		<li><strong>@Log.</strong> If you put this annotation on a method then Tapestry will write to the log, at DEBUG level, 
			as it enters and exits the method. Parameter values and the method's return value are logged too.<br/></li>
	</ul>
	
	Here is a demonstration:<br/>
	
	<div class="eg">
		message: "${message}".
	</div>

	References: 
	<a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/annotations.html">Annotations</a>, 
	<a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/logging.html">Logging</a>, 
